        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How Property Deposits Work in Queensland: What Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The deposit is one of the first things a buyer commits to. Understanding how it works, where it goes, and what happens if things change protects you through the campaign and into settlement.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Once a contract is signed, the buyer is required to pay a deposit. This is the financial commitment that backs up their signature. For sellers, understanding exactly how that money is handled, when you can access it, and what protections it provides is essential reading before you go to market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the deposit actually is</h2>
      <p>The deposit is the sum of money a buyer pays after signing the contract to demonstrate genuine commitment to completing the purchase. It is not a goodwill gesture or a booking fee. It is a legally binding financial obligation that sits within the contract of sale. In Queensland, the most common deposit amount is 10% of the purchase price, though 5% deposits are negotiated regularly, particularly when buyers are working with a broker and want to preserve cash before settlement. The deposit amount must be specified in the contract before signing.</p>

      <p>When the deposit is paid depends on the contract terms. The buyer typically has until the contract date or within a specified number of business days to transfer the funds. Your contract will state the exact deadline. If the deposit is not paid on time, you have grounds to issue a notice to remedy breach. This is another reason to engage a solicitor before you sign anything.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where your deposit goes (and why you can't touch it yet)</h2>
      <p>The deposit does not transfer to you at the point of sale. Under Queensland law, the funds are held in a statutory trust account, either by your real estate agent or by the buyer's solicitor, depending on how the contract is structured. Trust accounts are regulated by the Queensland Office of Fair Trading and are separate from the agent's operating funds. This is a legal protection for both parties, not a complication created by the agent.</p>

      <p>Premature release of the deposit requires the written agreement of both buyer and seller. Neither party can unilaterally access the funds while the contract is live. For sellers, this means you cannot use the deposit to fund a purchase or renovation before settlement. For buyers, it means they cannot withdraw the funds simply because they change their mind. The money sits in trust until the transaction completes or the contract is terminated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens at settlement</h2>
      <p>At settlement, the buyer pays the balance of the purchase price. Once the agent or conveyancer confirms settlement is complete, the deposit is released to you alongside that balance. From your perspective as a seller, settlement is the moment everything lands in your account at once. The deposit is not separately released beforehand under normal circumstances.</p>

      <p>This is worth understanding when you are doing your financial modelling. If you are relying on the proceeds to fund a simultaneous purchase, your solicitor needs to coordinate the timing carefully. The deposit alone does not unlock early access to your sale proceeds.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the buyer pulls out</h2>
      <p>The outcome depends entirely on why the buyer is exiting the contract.</p>

      <p>If the buyer exercises their cooling off right within the statutory period (five business days from contract signing in Queensland), they are entitled to the deposit back minus a penalty of 0.25% of the purchase price. This penalty goes to the seller. On a $900,000 purchase, that is $2,250. It compensates you for the time your property was off market, but it does not make you whole for a failed campaign.</p>

      <p>If the buyer pulls out because a valid condition in the contract has not been met, such as finance falling through or a building and pest inspection identifying a serious defect, the deposit is returned to the buyer in full. No penalty applies when a legitimate condition termination is exercised correctly. This is the most common scenario when contracts fall over in Brisbane's current market.</p>

      <p>If the buyer defaults after the contract goes unconditional, meaning all conditions have been waived and the settlement date is set, the situation is more serious. You may be entitled to forfeit the deposit as compensation. However, this is not automatic. You will need to issue a notice to remedy breach, give the buyer an opportunity to comply, and potentially pursue the matter through the courts if they do not settle. Your solicitor must guide this process. Acting without legal advice in this scenario is a significant risk.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the deposit size matters when you are negotiating</h2>
      <p>Not all buyers offer the same deposit, and the amount tells you something about their conviction. A buyer offering a 10% deposit has committed more financially and has more at risk if they walk away. A buyer offering 5% has less skin in the game. When you are evaluating competing offers or deciding whether to grant an extension, the deposit size is a meaningful data point alongside the price and the contract terms.</p>

      <p>In a multiple-offer situation, a buyer who offers a full 10% deposit alongside a strong price is signalling genuine commitment. A buyer who asks for an extended deposit payment period or a reduced deposit while also requesting conditions you are uncomfortable with deserves closer scrutiny. Deposits are not just administrative formalities. They are part of how you assess the quality of the buyer in front of you.</p>

